@node "Introduction" "Introduction"
@next "Features"
@prev "Main"

     This is a very simpel program to generate FILE_ID.DIZ files from
     the Aminet .readme file.

     DoDIZ will add the FILE_ID.DIZ generated file to your archive
     using external programs, so it's possible to configure DoDIZ
     with any archive program.

     It's also possible to specify the FILE_ID.DIZ output file with 
     different %-commands.

     The configuration is even more simple. You use the DoDIZ 
     @{"GUI preferences" link "Preferences" 0} to add new archivers and specify the FILE_ID.DIZ
     output file, no advanced config files...


     From the beginning I just made this program because I was tired
     of writing the Aminet descriptions for every file I uploaded to 
     my BBS. 
     After I had released my first version I got a very good respons 
     from users who liked it, so now it's already version 3.0 and
     DoDIZ gets more and more advanced with alot of @{"features" link "Features" 0}.
@endnode

@node "Features" "New Features"
@next "Requirements"
@prev "Introduction"

     New Features:
     ~~~~~~~~~~~~~

     DoDIZ v3.0 is totaly rewritten from earlier versions. DoDIZ is
     now more Amiga DOS specific to make it faster and safer.

     DoDIZ is mainly made to be used in scripts or just started from
     CLI, so there are @{"keywords" link "Keywords" 0} instead of a complete GUI, the @{"keywords" link "Keywords" 0}
     are now parsed with ReadArgs() instead of the ANSI argc/argv.

     DoDIZ is completly configurable with the DoDIZ @{"GUI preferences" link "Preferences" 0} so
     you can add any archiver by using external programs. It's also
     possible to specify the FILE_ID.DIZ format using %-commands which
     supports all Aminet keywords.


     Other features:

     o Possible to delete the .readme file after processed.

     o Possbile to include the .readme file in the archive.

     o Both Header and Footer file for the FILE_ID.DIZ.

     o You can also include filename, filesize, date and time
       in the FILE_ID.DIZ.

@endnode

@node "Requirements" "Requirements"
@next "Installation"
@prev "Features"

     Requirements:
     ~~~~~~~~~~~~~

     o You need OS2.0+.

     o reqtools.library v38+ © Nico Francois & Magnus Holmgren (Included).

     o Different archive programs and descript programs like:
       LHA, LZX, DMS, DoDescript (Included). Depending on what
       kind of archiver you like to add.

     o DoDIZ is tested on a Amiga 1200/030/18MB but there shouldn't
       be any problems, because DoDIZ uses the Amiga shared libraries.
@endnode

@node "Installation" "Installation"
@next "Usage"
@prev "Requirements"

     Installation:
     ~~~~~~~~~~~~~

     Use the included installation script or copy the files manual:

                  Bin/DoDIZ  - Somewhere in your path, for example C:.
          Prefs/DoDIZ.prefs  - S:.
        Prefs/DoDIZ.default  - ENV: and ENVARC:.
      Libs/reqtools.library  - LIBS:.


      In Headers/ there are some FILE_ID.DIZ headers, copy the one
      you like to S:DoDIZ.header. And in Footers/ there are some
      FILE_ID.DIZ Footers, copy one of them to S:DoDIZ.footer.
      It's NOT required to have a header or footer.

      NOTE: If you have a DoDIZ v2.0 header (DoDIZHead.TXT), rename
            it to DoDIZ.header.


      To be able to use the default settings, you MUST install 
      DoDescript v1.0. Copy the executable somewhere in your path.
@endnode

@node "Usage" "Usage"
@next "Keywords"
@prev "Installation"

     Usage:
     ~~~~~~

     DoDIZ is very simple, should be used from CLI, that's why there
     isn't a complete GUI program.

     Read @{"keywords" link "Keywords" 0} for complete description of the keywords.


     DoDIZ supports multiple files, (FILES/M). If you doesn't specify
     a file you will get a reqtools requester. DoDIZ also supports 
     wildcards like #?.LhA.

     DoDIZ ignores all .readme files even if you select them in the 
     reqtools requester. Remember the .readme has to be in the same
     directory as the file to process.


     Some examples:


        DoDIZ file.LhA file.LZX BOARDER DELREADME

     This will make DoDIZ process file.LhA and file.LZX in the current
     directory if there are any archivers configured for LhA and LZX. 
     DoDIZ will also make the FILE_ID.DIZ with the BOARDER keyword which 
     means that DoDIZ will assume that the first character at every row 
     specified in the FILE_ID.DIZ format is a boarder chararcter and then
     include that character at the last position at the row. (Read the 
     @{"keywords" link "Keywords" 0} part to see how BOARDER keyword works.)
     DoDIZ will also delete the readme files after processing them.


        DoDIZ DH3:AminetDownload/#?.LhA SKIPYES

     DoDIZ will process every .LhA file in DH3:AminetDownload and if 
     a FILE_ID.DIZ exists in any archive it will be skiped.


        DoDIZ #?

     Process all files in the current directory.


        DoDIZ PREFS

     Run the DoDIZ @{"GUI preference" link "Preferences" 0} program.



     o DoDIZ returncodes:

       OK     - 0
       WARN   - 5  
       ERROR  - 10
@endnode

@node "Keywords" "Keywords"
@next "Preferences"
@prev "Usage"

     Keywords:
     ~~~~~~~~~

     FILES/M

      The file(s) to be processed. Multiple fileselections is supported,
      also wildcards. If you doesn't specify any file at all, you will
      get a reqtools requester from where you can select your files.
      DoDIZ ignores the .readme files even if you select them in the
      reqtools requester. Remember that the .readme file has to be in
      the same directory as the file to be processed.


     NOHEADER/S

      This switch tells DoDIZ to skip the S:DoDIZ.header file, even
      if it exists.


     NOFOOTER/S

      This switch tells DoDIZ to skip the S:DoDIZ.footer file, even
      if it exists.


     BOARDER/S

      This switch tells DoDIZ to assume that the first character at every
      row in the FILE_ID.DIZ format is a boarder character, which means that
      the FILE_ID.DIZ will be shorted to 42 characters, and the boarder 
      character will also be included as the 44:th character at the end of the
      row.
      You can ofcause have different boarderchars for each row.


     ADDREADME/S

      This switch tells DoDIZ to add the .readme file to the archive.
      You will probably get error if the file isn't an archive. For example
      a textfile or a picture. It depends on how you have configured your
      archivers.


     DELREADME/S

      This switch tells DoDIZ to delete the .readme file after it's processed.


     SKIPYES/S

      This switch tells DoDIZ to assume yes to the query you get if the archive
      already has a FILE_ID.DIZ. Yes means that the FILE_ID.DIZ will be kept
      and the file is skiped.


     SKIPNO/S

      This switch tells DoDIZ to assume no to the query you get if the archive
      already has a FILE_ID.DIZ. No means that the FILE_ID.DIZ will be deleted
      and the DoDIZ FILE_ID.DIZ will be added instead.

     PREFS/S

      Runs the DoDIZ @{"GUI preferences" link "Preferences" 0}.
@endnode

@node "Preferences" "GUI Preferences"
@next "Note"
@prev "Keywords"

     GUI Preferences:
     ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

     DoDIZ supports a nice GUI for configuration of archivers and
     FILE_ID.DIZ output format.


     o Archivers:

     Here you add/remove archivers. The name of the archiver should be
     the file extension. DoDIZ doesn't do any checking if the file
     really are of the type specified.

     After adding a new archiver you select it in the listview, and then
     enter the commands for ADD/DELETE/EXTRACT for the archiver.

     %-Command for the archivers are:

      %a  - Archive filename. The file to be processed.

      %f  - Add/delete/extract filename. When you like to add/delete/extract
            a specific file with the archiver, this is where the filename
            should be placed. In other words this is the FILE_ID.DIZ file
            when DoDIZ adds/deletes/extracts internal.

      %o  - Output directory. This MUST be specified for the Extract
            command. And if your archiver doesn't support this you must
            pipe the file here named FILE_ID.DIZ. This is where the temporary
            FILE_ID.DIZ is placed.

     For example LhA has the command line:

       LhA [-<options>] <command> <archive[.LZH/LHA/RUN]> [[homedir]
            <filespec>...] [@file] [destdir]

     For Add command this means: LhA -q a %a %f
     and the Delete command: LhA -q d %a %f
     and the extract command: LhA -q e %a %f %o

     The -q option is just to make LhA quiet, it's good to do that if
     you doesn't like to see the archiver output, you can also pipe it
     NIL:.

     For example:

       LZX a %a %f >NIL: makes LZX quiet.


     If your file isn't really an archiver, for example textfiles and
     pictures you might have to pipe the FILE_ID.DIZ to the output
     directory, like this:

       DoDescript -q e %a >%oFILE_ID.DIZ

     This extracts the FILE_ID.DIZ to the ouput directory. or

       SnatchDIZ %a S >%oFILE_ID.DIZ  does the same thing.


     NOTE: DoDIZ always checks the returncode from the program, so even
           if a FILE_ID.DIZ file exists in the ouput directory DoDIZ
           will not process it if the program faild.

           For example for the two latest examples there will still be
           FILE_ID.DIZ in the ouput directory even if there wasn't any
           in the file, because the programs returns error outputs. But
           if the program returns an error code the FILE_ID.DIZ in the
           ouput directory will be ignored. This works fine with both
           DoDescript and SnatchDIZ.



     o FILE_ID.DIZ format:

     Here you specify the output format of the FILE_ID.DIZ to be created.

     All Aminet keywords are supported. After specified a %-command the
     rest of the row will be ignored. 

     If a keyword is to big to fit in the FILE_ID.DIZ it will not be filled 
     with it, except for Short: where the description will wordwraps if it 
     can't fit in the FILE_ID.DIZ.
     DoDIZ handles real wordwrapping so there will not be half words etc.

     For Uploder: and Author: DoDIZ DoDIZ wraps after the first space
     found, if the complete keywords is to big. That means for example:

       Uploader: kjellin@lysator.liu.se (Jonas Kjellin)

     Will wrap after the e-mail address if the complete line doesn't fit in.
     if the string still doesn't fit, the keyword will not be filled.

     Remember the keyword itself is not included in the sting returned.


     %-commands:

      %s  - Short:  Wordwraps if it doesn't fit.
      %u  - Uploader:  Wordwraps after the first space, if it doesn't fit.
      %a  - Author:  Wordwraps after the first space, if it doesen't fit.
      %t  - Type:  No wordwrapping, is not filled if it doesn't fit.
      %r  - Replaces:  No wordwrapping, is not filled if it doesn't fit.
      %q  - Requires:  No wordwrapping, is not filled if it doesn't fit.
      %v  - Version:  No wordwrapping, is not filled if it doesn't fit.
      %d  - Distribution:  No wordwrapping, is not filled if it doesn't fit.

     Special %-commands:

      %n  - Filename.
      %z  - Filesize in bytes (without the FILE_ID.DIZ).
      %e  - Date, Amiga DOS date (DD-MMM-YY) ex: 24-Feb-97.
      %i  - Time (HH:MM:SS).

     The date and time is when the FILE_ID.DIZ is created.

     The ouput format handles \n for new line.

     Examples:

     (The +----+ lines are shorted, should really be 44 characters)

     +--------------------+\n| Desc: %s\n|\n| Type: %s\n+-----------------+\n

     If the BOARDER @{"keyword" link "Keywords" 0} are specified it will look like this:

     +--------------------+
     | Desc: short desc   |
     |                    |
     | Type: type         |
     +--------------------+

     I know this is quite hard to see how the FILE_ID.DIZ output will look like
     so see the menu option "Convert txt -> FILE_ID.DIZ format".


     o Menu options:

       o Project menu

          About  - Some information how to contact me.
          Quit   - Quit DoDIZ GUI preferences.

       o Edit menu

          Duplicate Archive  

            Select a archive in the listview and choose this option, makes 
            you copy the archive settings to a new archive.


          Convert txt -> FILE_ID.DIZ format

            This lets you chose a textfile designed for the FILE_ID.DIZ
            format, including the %-commands and then converts it to
            single line format and includes it to the FILE_ID.DIZ format
            string gadget. The EOL in the textfile will be replaced
            with \n.


       o Edit menu

          Load settings     - Loads settings.
          Save settings     - Saves settings.
          Reset to default  - Resets settings to the default DoDIZ settings.
@endnode

@node "Note" "Note"
@next "Author"
@prev "Preferences"

     Note:
     ~~~~~

     o DoDIZ is made as a CLI program, I have got suggetsions to make
       a GUI for it, but as I like it to be a easy CLI command and be
       able to run it in scripts I think it's better like this.

       But if you out there like to have a GUI program that handles
       everything, I might do an external GUI program for DoDIZ so you
       can use it if you like.

     o If you have made some nice ASCII headers/footers, please send them
       to me and I might include them for the next version.

     o DoDIZ is Freeware, use it as much as you like...
       But I would be glad to get an e-mail from you if you use it.

     o Compiled with SAS C 6.57...
@endnode

